You're probably familiar with imports like that
 import { UsersListComponent } from '../../../ui/users-list/users-list.component.ts

And that doesn't look great. What can be done about it? 
We could try to add aliases in tsconfig.json like this
 {
   "paths": {
      "@myApp/ui": ["src/app/my-module/ui"]
    }
 }

and combine it with index.ts files in the users-list and ui folders
  export * from './users-list.component.ts';

Yes, that way an import could be turned into this
  import { UsersListComponent } from '@myApp/ui';

It will work if there's only one such a component. But probably "ui" general name implies at least several components (moreover with nested relationships), which could lead to a painful circular dependency error. So, what should we do? 
I came up with a solution. I'm not sure whether it's the best way (probably not, and if you know better way, I'd be more than happy to read about it in the comments). 
tsconfig into this:
 {
   ...
   "@myApp/ui/*" : "src/app/my-module/ui/*",
   ...
 }

And then import your component like this
 import { UsersListComponent } from '@myApp/ui/users-list';

by using index.ts file in the users-list folder we don't have to duplicate the same name ('users-list/users-list.component'), and by using asterisk sign (*) & aliases we're able to specify a particular folder avoiding circular dependency error. 
import { UserComponent } from '@myApp/ui/user';
import { AvatarComponent } from '@myApp/ui/avatar';
